Beverages are already subject to the sales tax in addition to the beverage tax created in the 1950s. West Virginians are taxed enough on beverages. Just because a tax hasn't been raised in 70 years doesn't mean it should be.

The West Virginia Beverage Association is AGAINST the proposed soft drink tax increase. Join our effort below: 

https://t.co/1HJpMssJKA

Remember the restaurants. The theaters. The entertainment venues. The stadiums, parks, and coliseums. These businesses were destroyed by COVID-19. Once they are fully reopened, customers could be welcomed back with higher sales taxes and beverage taxes. That is wrong.
Remember: If a beverage is not plain, flat water filtered and bottled, then it's most likely considered a soft drink in West Virginia. It's taxed twice.

Consider that many restaurants and small grocery stores have profit margins that are heavily dependent upon beverage sales. With a tax increase, sales will drop dramatically when West Virginians shop for their beverages outside the state or go to restaurants across the border.

The soft drink tax proposal is to increase the tax,  depending on how the beverage is produced or sold: 6 cents per 16.9 fluid-ounces beverage, a tax of $4.80 on each gallon of soft drink syrup or 6 cents for each 28.35 grams of dry mixture. That's not "upping it 5 cents a can."

We need to relieve burdens on our small businesses and families so they can recover, not add to their burdens with a regressive tax that hikes beverage prices as much as 500% and a state sales tax rate that would be the highest the country.
The beverage tax places a larger share of the tax burden on West Virginians least capable of paying it.

If these waters are in your hand this morning, then you paid a sales tax and a soft drink tax. Why? The water contains vitamins. That makes it a soft drink in WV. That tax could increase by as much as 500%. It’s not a soda tax— it’s not a pop tax. It’s a beverage tax. Be aware. https://t.co/9fjQJZJQIk

The proposed increase on the beverage tax would be up to 500% of what it is now. Working families are going to feel that surge in grocery bills, on top of a sales tax increase that would be the highest in the country.

West Virginians are going to be shocked with they see how many beverage items are considered to be soft drinks in West Virginia and taxed twice: once by a sales tax (which could go up), and then by the soft drink tax (which could go up by as much as 500%).

These beverages are taxed as a soft drink in WV. The can of sparkling water is taxed because it contains natural lime. Be aware of what the beverage tax entails. It may go up, and on products that are not soda. https://t.co/e8ozlGdHYD
